WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:08.870
So this class and the next
class and a half are going to be

00:00:08.870 --> 00:00:16.850
about Fisher's theory of present
value and the interest rate,

00:00:16.850 --> 00:00:21.460
and then we're going to move to
uncertainty.

00:00:21.460 --> 00:00:24.588
So up until now what we've done
is we found out first,

00:00:24.588 --> 00:00:27.775
if you know the whole economic
system, how to solve for

00:00:27.775 --> 00:00:28.720
equilibrium.
 

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:31.570
To figure out from the
primitives of people's tastes,

00:00:31.570 --> 00:00:33.701
their impatience,
the technology,

00:00:33.701 --> 00:00:36.393
the economy,
how to figure out the real rate

00:00:36.393 --> 00:00:39.834
of interest if provided there is
no uncertainty in the world and

00:00:39.834 --> 00:00:42.730
people can forecast what is
going to happen later.

00:00:42.730 --> 00:00:45.270
We've found that once you've
done that,

00:00:45.270 --> 00:00:47.947
the price of every asset,
if people are rational and

00:00:47.947 --> 00:00:51.403
looking forward to the future,
the price of every asset is

00:00:51.403 --> 00:00:55.105
going to be the present value of
the future payments of the

00:00:55.105 --> 00:00:55.680
asset.
 

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:58.172
So if you think of the payments
as real payments,

00:00:58.172 --> 00:01:01.234
which is what Fisher always
recommended, you discount by the

00:01:01.234 --> 00:01:02.429
real interest rate.
 

00:01:02.429 --> 00:01:05.346
If you think of them as cash
payments then you discount by

00:01:05.346 --> 00:01:06.780
the nominal interest rate.
 

00:01:06.780 --> 00:01:11.376
So every asset corresponds to
its present value of its

00:01:11.376 --> 00:01:16.409
dividends either discounted by
the real rate or the nominal

00:01:16.409 --> 00:01:17.188
rate.
 

00:01:17.188 --> 00:01:23.188
Now, this thinking is
surprisingly powerful and leads

00:01:23.188 --> 00:01:26.879
you to unexpected conclusions.
 

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:29.438
So the next two classes is
about that.

00:01:29.438 --> 00:01:32.150
Mostly I'm going to talk about
Social Security,

00:01:32.150 --> 00:01:35.510
but I'm going to begin today by
finishing off a subject we

00:01:35.510 --> 00:01:37.810
didn't quite get through last
time.

00:01:37.810 --> 00:01:42.007
So you see, if you realize that
the price of every asset is just

00:01:42.007 --> 00:01:44.540
the present value of its
dividends,

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:47.391
and you also suppose you know
what the dividends are going to

00:01:47.391 --> 00:01:50.099
be and what the future interest
rates are going to be,

00:01:50.099 --> 00:01:53.471
then it follows that you know
what the price of the asset is

00:01:53.471 --> 00:01:55.063
going to be,
not just today,

00:01:55.063 --> 00:01:57.265
but next year,
and the year after and the year

00:01:57.265 --> 00:01:57.950
after that.
 

00:01:57.950 --> 00:02:00.400
So your theory of asset pricing
today,

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:02.837
which was based on the
assumption that you can forecast

00:02:02.837 --> 00:02:05.221
the future,
necessarily implies the theory

00:02:05.221 --> 00:02:07.090
of asset pricing in the future.
 

00:02:07.090 --> 00:02:10.397
So you can tell something about
how asset prices are going to

00:02:10.397 --> 00:02:12.437
change,
and of course you can also test

00:02:12.437 --> 00:02:15.031
the theory because the theory
implicitly is forecasting

00:02:15.031 --> 00:02:19.125
something about the future,
and therefore you can test the

00:02:19.125 --> 00:02:19.818
theory.
 

00:02:19.818 --> 00:02:25.310
So let's just take a couple
examples that are in the notes.

00:02:25.310 --> 00:02:27.520
So we said at the top,
if you can read it,

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:31.407
I hope it's not too small--I
want to move a little quickly so

00:02:31.407 --> 00:02:34.000
I could be writing this on the
board,

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:42.020
but if you can see it and you
look at the top line it says

00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:50.324
that the present value of the
assets is just the discount of

00:02:50.324 --> 00:02:53.280
future dividends.
 

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:58.298
So maybe I'll start one line
up, actually,

00:02:58.298 --> 00:03:00.378
in these notes.
 

00:03:00.378 --> 00:03:02.701
So if you look in the middle
here the present value today,

00:03:02.701 --> 00:03:05.025
suppose you have an asset,
maybe I'm going to write on the

00:03:05.025 --> 00:03:05.840
board after all.
 

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:09.373
Present value of an asset,
suppose you know the dividends

00:03:09.373 --> 00:03:13.034
are going to be paying C (1),
C (2), and maybe C (T) at the

00:03:13.034 --> 00:03:13.538
end.
 

00:03:13.538 --> 00:03:16.532
Those are the dividends that
are going to be paid,

00:03:16.532 --> 00:03:19.770
and you can ask what the
present value of the asset is

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:21.908
today, PV_0 today,
0.

00:03:21.908 --> 00:03:26.117
Well, Fisher would say if you
think of these as nominal cash

00:03:26.117 --> 00:03:30.468
flows he would say what you need
to do is you need to find out

00:03:30.468 --> 00:03:32.110
the price of zeros.
 

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:37.657
So you recall that Fisher said
that you could let

00:03:37.657 --> 00:03:44.360
pi_1 = the price today
of 1 dollar at time 1,

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:49.268
and the price today
pi_T = the price today

00:03:49.268 --> 00:03:51.288
of 1 dollar time T.
 

00:03:51.288 --> 00:03:55.470
It's the price today of 1
dollar in the future.

00:03:55.470 --> 00:03:58.365
These were the crucial prices
that Fisher said that you should

00:03:58.365 --> 00:03:59.220
always look for.
 

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:01.941
He said that you can always
find these prices,

00:04:01.941 --> 00:04:05.146
pi_1 through
pi_T by deriving them

00:04:05.146 --> 00:04:06.658
from the yield curve.
 

00:04:06.658 --> 00:04:10.471
So every morning everybody
looks at the yield curve,

00:04:10.471 --> 00:04:14.133
all financial analysts,
they look at the prices of

00:04:14.133 --> 00:04:16.449
bonds traded in the market.
 

00:04:16.449 --> 00:04:19.629
The simplest form is you get a
yield curve in the newspapers.

00:04:19.629 --> 00:04:22.074
You deduce from the yield curve
what these present values

00:04:22.074 --> 00:04:24.153
pi_1,
pi_T are,

00:04:24.153 --> 00:04:28.108
and that allows you to price
any asset like this one simply

00:04:28.108 --> 00:04:30.629
by multiplying by
pi_1,

00:04:30.629 --> 00:04:35.949
pi_2 and at the end
by pi_T.

00:04:35.949 --> 00:04:38.230
So that's step 1.
 

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:41.028
But then step 2,
we said, was that once you've

00:04:41.028 --> 00:04:44.199
got these prices you can figure
out the forwards.

00:04:44.199 --> 00:04:54.259
So the forwards are going to be
1 i_t,

00:04:54.259 --> 00:05:06.675
so 1 i_t that's by
definition the interest from t

00:05:06.675 --> 00:05:14.810
to t 1 that would be agreed
today.

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:17.653
It's not the interest rate
that's going to prevail from

00:05:17.653 --> 00:05:19.997
time t,
it's the interest rate that

00:05:19.997 --> 00:05:23.971
people today at time 0 would
agree to pay between time t and

00:05:23.971 --> 00:05:24.778
time t 1.
 

00:05:24.778 --> 00:05:27.461
So that, of course,
has to just equal

00:05:27.461 --> 00:05:30.439
pi_t over pi_t
1,

00:05:30.439 --> 00:05:33.254
because everybody today
recognizes that the cost of a

00:05:33.254 --> 00:05:36.589
dollar time t is pi_t,
and the cost of a dollar at

00:05:36.589 --> 00:05:38.190
time t 1 is pi_t 1.
 

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:41.644
So the tradeoff between t and t
1 that's effectively what an

00:05:41.644 --> 00:05:44.923
interest rate does is it trades
off money at one time for

00:05:44.923 --> 00:05:45.920
another time.
 

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:47.220
It has to be this ratio.
 

00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:50.144
So today people would agree on
1 i_t^(F),

00:05:50.144 --> 00:05:51.959
forward, as the forward rate.
 

00:05:51.959 --> 00:05:59.201
Now, you add to that the
assumption that everybody is

00:05:59.201 --> 00:06:06.860
certain about the future,
assume perfect forecasting.

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:09.728
So I don't have to actually
assume people are right in their

00:06:09.728 --> 00:06:10.410
forecasting.
 

00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:12.720
I have to assume that they are
completely sure of their

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:13.319
forecasting.
 

00:06:13.319 --> 00:06:16.773
So if they're completely sure
of their forecasting then

00:06:16.773 --> 00:06:20.545
everybody must foresee that they
think they're sure that the

00:06:20.545 --> 00:06:24.447
future interest rate that will
prevail at time t is also equal

00:06:24.447 --> 00:06:25.790
to this number.
 

00:06:25.790 --> 00:06:34.230
So we can then rewrite this
price.

00:06:34.230 --> 00:06:35.110
Hello.
 

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:40.985
We can rewrite this price as 1
i_0^(F),

00:06:40.985 --> 00:06:44.336
forward;
instead of pi_2,

00:06:44.336 --> 00:06:49.411
pi_2 is just going to
be 1 over (1 i_0^(F))

00:06:49.411 --> 00:06:55.016
times (1 i_1^(F)),
and time pi_T is just

00:06:55.016 --> 00:06:59.641
going to be 1 over (1
i_0^(F)) times (1

00:06:59.641 --> 00:07:02.050
i_1^(F)) ...
 

00:07:02.050 --> 00:07:10.990
times (1 i_t 1^(F)).
 

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:17.634
Because using the fact that (1
i_t) is pi_t

00:07:17.634 --> 00:07:23.742
divided by pi_t 1 I
just multiply pi_1

00:07:23.742 --> 00:07:29.744
divided by pi_2 times
pi_2 divided by

00:07:29.744 --> 00:07:32.959
pi_0 etcetera.
 

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:37.776
If I take pi_1
divided by pi_0 times

00:07:37.776 --> 00:07:42.069
etcetera I'm going to get
exactly this formula.

00:07:42.069 --> 00:07:52.410
So pi_0 is always 1,
by the way.

00:07:52.410 --> 00:07:54.880
So if I want to take
pi_1 it's just going

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:56.709
to be 1 over (1
i_0^(F)).

00:07:56.709 --> 00:08:02.127
If I want to take
pi_2 I can always do

00:08:02.127 --> 00:08:03.755
this,
pi_2,

00:08:03.755 --> 00:08:05.970
and so this is going to equal
pi_2,

00:08:05.970 --> 00:08:09.574
so pi_2 is going to
be 1 over (1 i^(F)_0)

00:08:09.574 --> 00:08:12.338
times 1 over (1
i^(F)_1) etcetera.

00:08:12.338 --> 00:08:14.319
And pi_3,
if I want to do pi_3,

00:08:14.319 --> 00:08:16.690
I just multiply by
pi_3 over

00:08:16.690 --> 00:08:19.639
pi_2 and so that's
equal to 1 over (1

00:08:19.639 --> 00:08:23.485
i^(F)_0) times 1 over
(1 i^(F)_1) times 1

00:08:23.485 --> 00:08:25.600
over (1 i^(F)_2).
 

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:28.389
So instead of multiplying by
the pis I may as well take the

00:08:28.389 --> 00:08:29.639
product of the forwards.
 

00:08:29.639 --> 00:08:31.100
It's exactly the same thing.
 

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:35.889
So the present value has this
simple formula,

00:08:35.889 --> 00:08:39.341
but this is a formula that
holds at every time t if you're

00:08:39.341 --> 00:08:42.794
totally confident of your
predictions of the Cs and of the

00:08:42.794 --> 00:08:44.370
future interest rates.
 

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:49.570
This is where we ended last
time, basically with this

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:50.570
formula.
 

00:08:50.570 --> 00:08:53.495
The key that you had to use in
the problem set was to realize

00:08:53.495 --> 00:08:56.519
if you're totally confident now
about the future you have to be

00:08:56.519 --> 00:08:59.690
totally confident about doing
this calculation in the future.

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:03.423
So PV_1 is going to
be basically the same

00:09:03.423 --> 00:09:04.470
calculation.
 

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:07.019
So what's going to happen at
time 1?

00:09:07.019 --> 00:09:10.505
After you've gone down 1 year
you've finished with this

00:09:10.505 --> 00:09:14.509
interest rate and you're looking
at everything 1 year later.

00:09:14.509 --> 00:09:20.495
So I may as well write the
PV_1 here and that's

00:09:20.495 --> 00:09:25.208
going to equal C (2)--
let's put it a little bit

00:09:25.208 --> 00:09:30.024
lower--PV_1 is going
to equal the same C (2) as

00:09:30.024 --> 00:09:32.389
before,
but now a year later.

00:09:32.389 --> 00:09:37.830
So it's just going to be 1
i^(F)_1 C (T),

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:43.379
and I don't need the 1
i^(F)_0 anymore.

00:09:43.379 --> 00:09:48.589
(1 i^(F)_1) times ...
 

00:09:48.589 --> 00:09:52.788
(1 i^(F)_T-1).
 

00:09:52.788 --> 00:09:55.384
So it's exactly the same
formula 1 year later,

00:09:55.384 --> 00:09:58.960
and 1 year later you no longer
have to worry about the interest

00:09:58.960 --> 00:09:59.480
rate.
 

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:01.158
That time already passed.
 

00:10:01.158 --> 00:10:04.410
So you just drop this at every
time and you write the same

00:10:04.410 --> 00:10:07.548
formula, and of course you drop
C (1) because that's all

00:10:07.548 --> 00:10:08.288
finished.
 

00:10:08.288 --> 00:10:13.499
So the price at time 1 is just
what's left except you've

00:10:13.499 --> 00:10:18.139
chopped off the 1
i^(F)_0 everywhere.

00:10:18.139 --> 00:10:25.374
So to write that the same way,
so PV_0 (I can write

00:10:25.374 --> 00:10:30.678
it the same way) =,
PV_0 = what?

00:10:30.678 --> 00:10:33.658
It's going to equal the
interest payment you get,

00:10:33.658 --> 00:10:35.649
C (1), not the interest,
the dividend you get,

00:10:35.649 --> 00:10:46.982
the cash flow you get plus
PV_1 divided by 1

00:10:46.982 --> 00:10:51.259
i^(F)_0.
 

00:10:51.259 --> 00:10:53.440
So this is a very important
formula.

00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:56.129
So why is that?
 

00:10:56.129 --> 00:11:01.597
Well, it's a proof by formula,
but another way of saying it is

00:11:01.597 --> 00:11:05.490
that PV_0,
when you get the asset at time

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:07.870
0 it gives you a cash flow at
time 1,

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:10.498
and then of course looked at
from the point of view of time 1

00:11:10.498 --> 00:11:12.250
you've got all the future cash
flows,

00:11:12.250 --> 00:11:14.080
but that's just what
PV_1 is.

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:18.211
So basically the bond is going
to give you a cash flow at time

00:11:18.211 --> 00:11:19.924
1,
and then the right to cash

00:11:19.924 --> 00:11:22.606
flows in the future,
but this right to cash flows in

00:11:22.606 --> 00:11:24.860
the future at time 1 is worth
PV_1.

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:28.009
So it's like you've got all
this money at time 1 and so to

00:11:28.009 --> 00:11:31.379
get the value at time 0 you have
to discount it back again.

00:11:31.379 --> 00:11:38.283
So this is a very famous and
important formula which I want

00:11:38.283 --> 00:11:42.570
to pause a second and think
about.

00:11:42.570 --> 00:11:56.720
So there's a controversy today
called marking to market.

00:11:56.720 --> 00:12:00.870
Does anybody know what that
controversy is about?

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:02.029
What does marking to market
mean?

00:12:02.029 --> 00:12:03.509
Yep?
 

00:12:03.509 --> 00:12:07.053
Student: I believe that
it means that corporations and

00:12:07.053 --> 00:12:10.184
their accounting rules are
currently required to value

00:12:10.184 --> 00:12:13.907
their assets at what they would
fetch in the market if they were

00:12:13.907 --> 00:12:15.028
to sell them.
 

00:12:15.028 --> 00:12:19.844
Prof: Right,
but you know that they've been

00:12:19.844 --> 00:12:24.070
relieved of this responsibility
recently.

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:24.908
Student: No,
I didn't know that.

00:12:24.908 --> 00:12:26.812
Prof: Well,
so they've been relieved of

00:12:26.812 --> 00:12:28.038
this responsibility lately.
 

00:12:28.038 --> 00:12:29.830
Now, why have they been
relieved of it?

00:12:29.830 --> 00:12:33.182
Because the thought was that
the market was so panicked in

00:12:33.182 --> 00:12:36.535
the crisis that the price that
they could fetch by selling

00:12:36.535 --> 00:12:39.889
their things really had nothing
to do with the value.

00:12:39.889 --> 00:12:43.732
So we're going to come back to
whether that was a good idea

00:12:43.732 --> 00:12:46.980
that Congress passed under
tremendous pressure.

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:50.360
What is the point of marking to
market?

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:52.770
So let's suppose that you
really could anticipate the

00:12:52.770 --> 00:12:54.720
future and everybody was right
about it.

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:58.928
The market price then would
really be PV_0 today,

00:12:58.928 --> 00:13:01.340
and it really would be
PV_1 tomorrow,

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:03.988
because if the interest rate's
do actually turn out to be what

00:13:03.988 --> 00:13:06.110
everybody expects,
and everybody's completely

00:13:06.110 --> 00:13:09.254
confident of their expectation,
then as we saw the prices would

00:13:09.254 --> 00:13:11.428
have to be this today and this
tomorrow,

00:13:11.428 --> 00:13:12.538
otherwise there'd be an
arbitrage.

00:13:12.538 --> 00:13:15.009
You could make money for sure,
or think you could make money

00:13:15.009 --> 00:13:15.470
for sure.
 

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:19.721
So if you're marking to market
what are you going to mark as

00:13:19.721 --> 00:13:20.730
the profits?
 

00:13:20.730 --> 00:13:28.259
Are you going to say the profit
at time 1 is--so what is profit?

00:13:28.259 --> 00:13:30.159
If I had some room I'd put this
somewhere.

00:13:30.159 --> 00:13:35.620
How would you define profit?
 

00:13:35.620 --> 00:13:36.590
I'll get rid of this.
 

00:13:36.590 --> 00:13:38.870
I think we've got this straight.
 

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:52.870
 
 

00:13:52.870 --> 00:14:00.080
So how would you define profit
at time 1?

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:07.690
What would you write?
 

00:14:07.690 --> 00:14:09.269
So let's say that this isn't a
bond.

00:14:09.269 --> 00:14:11.230
It's an investment.
 

00:14:11.230 --> 00:14:14.903
You paid a bunch of money at
time 0, maybe PV_0 and

00:14:14.903 --> 00:14:18.759
in the future your investment is
going to pay off some money.

00:14:18.759 --> 00:14:20.460
Maybe it was a project you
invested in.

00:14:20.460 --> 00:14:23.168
Maybe you bought a bunch of
stuff and you're selling it in

00:14:23.168 --> 00:14:24.879
the future and getting this
money.

00:14:24.879 --> 00:14:27.288
Maybe you bought a bond which
is paying these coupons.

00:14:27.288 --> 00:14:29.918
Whatever it is these are the
cash flows of the project,

00:14:29.918 --> 00:14:32.450
and now of course your
investors are very curious.

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:35.192
In year 1, they want to know
what profit have you made,

00:14:35.192 --> 00:14:36.210
how are you doing?
 

00:14:36.210 --> 00:14:38.629
So what's a number that you'd
think of giving?

00:14:38.629 --> 00:14:40.500
What's the first number you'd
think of telling them?

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:41.259
Yep?
 

00:14:41.259 --> 00:14:43.340
Student: Maybe the first
cash flow payout.

00:14:43.340 --> 00:14:50.289
Prof: So you might think
of saying, C (1).

00:14:50.289 --> 00:14:51.830
That's the cash you've gotten.
 

00:14:51.830 --> 00:14:54.860
So all these people could see
you've gotten C (1).

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:58.004
That's your revenue,
and I'm assuming this cash flow

00:14:58.004 --> 00:14:59.298
is net of expenses.
 

00:14:59.298 --> 00:15:02.600
So you could say here's your
revenue you got at time 1,

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:03.090
C (1).
 

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:04.759
Is that your profit?
 

00:15:04.759 --> 00:15:07.149
If it were, people would then
look and they'd say,

00:15:07.149 --> 00:15:11.875
"Well, we got profit of C
(1) and we put an investment in

00:15:11.875 --> 00:15:15.750
of PV_0 so is that the
rate of return?

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:24.639
Is that my rate of return?"
 

00:15:24.639 --> 00:15:25.860
Yeah?
 

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:28.720
Student: Can we do
PV_1 - PV_0

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:29.639
and add it here?
 

00:15:29.639 --> 00:15:33.840
Prof: So he's exactly
right.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:37.515
I'm going to repeat what he
said, but I'm going to take

00:15:37.515 --> 00:15:38.808
longer to say it.
 

00:15:38.808 --> 00:15:43.511
This idea of writing C (1) over
PV_0 is actually what

00:15:43.511 --> 00:15:48.062
many people try to say is their
profit, but it's a bad number

00:15:48.062 --> 00:15:49.200
for profit.
 

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:53.058
Now, if in period 1 you stopped
marking to market,

00:15:53.058 --> 00:15:55.759
and you had no idea,
you didn't have to report this

00:15:55.759 --> 00:15:58.287
number PV_1,
I mean, you didn't know what it

00:15:58.287 --> 00:15:59.730
was or you didn't have to report
it,

00:15:59.730 --> 00:16:03.572
what else could you report but
C (1) over PV_0 as the

00:16:03.572 --> 00:16:04.129
profit?
 

00:16:04.129 --> 00:16:06.735
So marking to market,
you see, is intimately

00:16:06.735 --> 00:16:08.980
connected to how you report
profit.

00:16:08.980 --> 00:16:10.975
So if you don't mark to market
you don't know,

00:16:10.975 --> 00:16:13.722
you don't have to declare what
the value of the assets are that

00:16:13.722 --> 00:16:14.298
are left.
 

00:16:14.298 --> 00:16:17.307
All you would do when you
describe your profits is you'd

00:16:17.307 --> 00:16:19.836
say C (1) and people would,
of course, in their heads,

00:16:19.836 --> 00:16:21.370
in fact they wouldn't do it in
their heads,

00:16:21.370 --> 00:16:24.571
you'd tell them,
"Our rate of return was C

00:16:24.571 --> 00:16:28.607
(1) over PV_0,"
but why might that be a very

00:16:28.607 --> 00:16:30.139
misleading number?
 

00:16:30.139 --> 00:16:34.803
Well, his point is it could
well be that C (1) is a very

00:16:34.803 --> 00:16:35.990
high number.
 

00:16:35.990 --> 00:16:40.398
You've got a lot of cash flow
this period, but he said it may

00:16:40.398 --> 00:16:44.220
turn out that PV_1 is
a terrible number.

00:16:44.220 --> 00:16:47.669
You may have gotten a lot of
cash flow, but there's nothing

00:16:47.669 --> 00:16:48.918
left going forward.
 

00:16:48.918 --> 00:16:53.548
So he doesn't think that's a
very good measure of profit.

00:16:53.548 --> 00:17:02.107
So he's suggesting why not
report profit as C (1)

00:17:02.107 --> 00:17:08.170
PV_1 - PV_0.
 

00:17:08.170 --> 00:17:11.710
Now, suppose you did that?
 

00:17:11.710 --> 00:17:13.814
So he's saying,
look, you've got a certain

00:17:13.814 --> 00:17:16.894
amount of cash but the assets
that you had also changed value

00:17:16.894 --> 00:17:19.410
and you ought to include that in
your profit.

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:21.430
So what if you did that?
 

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:25.269
What would your rate of return
be?

00:17:25.269 --> 00:17:28.423
And suppose PV_0 and
PV_1 were calculated

00:17:28.423 --> 00:17:28.950
as this?
 

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:31.496
And so you divided this by
PV_0 what would that

00:17:31.496 --> 00:17:31.859
equal?
 

00:17:31.859 --> 00:17:52.068
 
 

00:17:52.068 --> 00:17:58.420
What number would I get if I
did that?

00:17:58.420 --> 00:17:59.130
I can't hear.
 

00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:00.890
What?
 

00:18:00.890 --> 00:18:03.190
Somebody speak up.
 

00:18:03.190 --> 00:18:05.640
Student:
i^(F)_0.

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:06.960
Prof: Yes.
 

00:18:06.960 --> 00:18:09.798
This would just be
i^(F)_0,

00:18:09.798 --> 00:18:14.690
and you get the rate of return
that you're expecting to get.

00:18:14.690 --> 00:18:16.710
Now, how do I know that's
i^(F)_0?

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:19.896
Because I multiplied by
PV_0 to this side,

00:18:19.896 --> 00:18:22.646
then I moved that
PV_0 to the other

00:18:22.646 --> 00:18:23.210
side.
 

00:18:23.210 --> 00:18:26.146
That gives me 1
i_0^(F)

00:18:26.146 --> 00:18:29.272
PV_0,
then I divide by that 1

00:18:29.272 --> 00:18:31.900
i^(F)_0 and put it
down here,

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:34.960
and that's this formula.
 

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:37.910
So that is what you would get,
i^(F)_0.

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:40.156
And you see that's what you
should expect to get because you

00:18:40.156 --> 00:18:41.299
haven't done anything great.
 

00:18:41.299 --> 00:18:42.440
You've got a cash flow.
 

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:45.098
You've got these cash flows at
the beginning.

00:18:45.098 --> 00:18:48.143
You paid a fair price for them
and next period everybody

00:18:48.143 --> 00:18:51.630
forecast that the values were
going to go to PV_1,

00:18:51.630 --> 00:18:53.559
and so it can't be that you're,
you know--

00:18:53.559 --> 00:18:54.890
this was an investment you made.
 

00:18:54.890 --> 00:18:55.779
You put your money in.
 

00:18:55.779 --> 00:18:57.240
You bought this bond.
 

00:18:57.240 --> 00:19:00.893
You could sell the bond now at
time 1 after having obtained the

00:19:00.893 --> 00:19:01.660
cash flows.
 

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:04.753
It better be that your rate of
return is the market interest

00:19:04.753 --> 00:19:07.375
rate of return otherwise there'd
be some arbitrage,

00:19:07.375 --> 00:19:08.528
and in fact it is.
 

00:19:08.528 --> 00:19:12.126
So if you can compute all the
present values properly,

00:19:12.126 --> 00:19:16.200
the only fair thing to do--this
is not a great investment.

00:19:16.200 --> 00:19:19.486
Even if C (1) is a huge amount
of money it's only huge because

00:19:19.486 --> 00:19:21.750
PV_1 is a low amount
of money.

00:19:21.750 --> 00:19:24.078
Because it has to be that the
profit every period,

00:19:24.078 --> 00:19:26.385
the rate of profit,
is exactly equal to the

00:19:26.385 --> 00:19:29.766
interest rate,
because everything is always

00:19:29.766 --> 00:19:32.298
priced at its present value.
 

00:19:32.298 --> 00:19:40.849
So it's a simple concept which
somehow takes a long time to

00:19:40.849 --> 00:19:42.029
grasp.
 

00:19:42.029 --> 00:19:46.198
It just seems to people
that--here's the money that's

00:19:46.198 --> 00:19:47.000
come in.
 

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:48.920
That's the cash you can count
in your hands.

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:49.858
You've got it in your hands.
 

00:19:49.858 --> 00:19:52.236
That's the number you should
talk about as profit,

00:19:52.236 --> 00:19:55.000
but of course of the money
coming into your hands--there's

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.358
this other hidden thing.
 

00:19:56.358 --> 00:19:58.938
The stuff that you own has
suddenly fallen in value

00:19:58.938 --> 00:20:00.640
compared to what it was before.
 

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:03.365
You're really not putting the
firm in any better position than

00:20:03.365 --> 00:20:04.078
it was before.
 

00:20:04.078 --> 00:20:07.000
You just earned your normal
rate of return.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:13.480
So you can see why,
to give a fair description of

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:17.951
how people are doing,
the law was written,

00:20:17.951 --> 00:20:21.397
evolved to the point where
people were forced not to just

00:20:21.397 --> 00:20:23.729
say C (1),
they were forced to

00:20:23.729 --> 00:20:27.305
declare--mark to market,
and add PV_1 -

00:20:27.305 --> 00:20:31.348
PV_0 to their profit
to get a real rate of return,

00:20:31.348 --> 00:20:37.240
to get a more revealing rate of
return.

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:40.277
And so what happened in the
crisis is this PV_1

00:20:40.277 --> 00:20:43.205
became such a horribly low
number that if you plug that

00:20:43.205 --> 00:20:46.190
into this formula you get
PV_1 is a really low

00:20:46.190 --> 00:20:48.359
number compared to
PV_0.

00:20:48.359 --> 00:20:49.769
You get a giant negative here.
 

00:20:49.769 --> 00:20:53.769
It would look like the rate of
return was terrible.

00:20:53.769 --> 00:20:56.930
Everyone would panic and think
the firms had fallen apart.

00:20:56.930 --> 00:21:00.506
So especially the banks were
the ones who didn't want to do

00:21:00.506 --> 00:21:02.926
this,
and so Congress didn't want the

00:21:02.926 --> 00:21:05.539
public to be panicked so it
simply said,

00:21:05.539 --> 00:21:07.000
"Okay, forget about it.
 

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:09.953
We're going to not hold you to
writing PV_1 anymore

00:21:09.953 --> 00:21:12.808
because we can't count anybody
figuring out what it is,

00:21:12.808 --> 00:21:15.298
and so you don't have to tell
us that.

00:21:15.298 --> 00:21:17.500
You just have to tell us
this," which happens to be

00:21:17.500 --> 00:21:20.205
a good number for the banks,
but that doesn't mean the banks

00:21:20.205 --> 00:21:23.092
are actually doing well because
the assets they hold have been

00:21:23.092 --> 00:21:24.180
collapsing in value.
 

00:21:24.180 --> 00:21:24.259
Yeah?
 

00:21:24.259 --> 00:21:26.775
Student: Does that
&gt;

00:21:26.775 --> 00:21:29.742
say that assuming there's no
arbitrage opportunity if a firm

00:21:29.742 --> 00:21:32.460
pays out a high dividend its
stock should go down?

00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:34.509
Prof: Yes, right.
 

00:21:34.509 --> 00:21:36.930
That's exactly what it says and
that's what does happen.

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:39.910
So you always talk about the
price, ex-dividend and stuff

00:21:39.910 --> 00:21:41.400
like that, precisely that.
 

00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:44.019
So if a firm pays a bigger than
usual dividend,

00:21:44.019 --> 00:21:47.852
if it suddenly decides it's
going to pay itself a gigantic

00:21:47.852 --> 00:21:51.818
dividend then the price of the
firm is going to go down,

00:21:51.818 --> 00:21:55.808
exactly, because there's less
value in the firm.

00:21:55.808 --> 00:21:58.450
You've paid it out here instead
of keeping it into the firm.

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:00.909
So this is a very simple idea,
but it's very easy to get

00:22:00.909 --> 00:22:01.670
confused about.
 

00:22:01.670 --> 00:22:05.779
Are there any questions about
it?

00:22:05.779 --> 00:22:08.140
So let's do an example of it.
 

00:22:08.140 --> 00:22:14.088
The most basic example of it is
the premium bond.

00:22:14.088 --> 00:22:16.519
So we talked about this before,
the premium bond.

00:22:16.519 --> 00:22:21.650
So let's say you have
PV_0 = 5 divided by

00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:26.061
1.10 5 divided by 1.10
[correction: squared]

00:22:26.061 --> 00:22:30.680
(maybe this was exactly the
problem set,

00:22:30.680 --> 00:22:33.193
I can't remember) 105 divided
by 1.10 [correction:

00:22:33.193 --> 00:22:33.808
to the T].
 

00:22:33.808 --> 00:22:39.653
So in other words the interest
rate--I did that wrong--squared

00:22:39.653 --> 00:22:40.420
and T.
 

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:43.118
So the forwards,
in other words,

00:22:43.118 --> 00:22:47.212
1 i^(F)_t (small t) =
1 .10 for all t,

00:22:47.212 --> 00:22:50.608
so all the forwards are 10
percent.

00:22:50.608 --> 00:22:54.579
The bond is paying--I can't
remember which one I did.

00:22:54.579 --> 00:22:57.210
Let's do 20 here.
 

00:22:57.210 --> 00:23:02.480
I'm going to make it a premium
bond, so it's paying 20.

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:09.848
So what's going to be the price
of the bond?

00:23:09.848 --> 00:23:12.463
Well, in the first period it
looks like you get this

00:23:12.463 --> 00:23:13.490
incredible profit.
 

00:23:13.490 --> 00:23:15.038
The interest rate is 10 percent.
 

00:23:15.038 --> 00:23:19.278
You've paid some present value
and you've made 20.

00:23:19.278 --> 00:23:21.867
You've made a number much
bigger--so the price of this

00:23:21.867 --> 00:23:24.359
thing, by the way what was the
home work problem?

00:23:24.359 --> 00:23:26.660
What were the numbers?
 

00:23:26.660 --> 00:23:31.180
What was the interest rate?
 

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:32.618
Did somebody do the homework?
 

00:23:32.618 --> 00:23:34.702
I did assign a homework on a
premium bond,

00:23:34.702 --> 00:23:35.108
right?
 

00:23:35.108 --> 00:23:38.457
The interest rate was 5 percent
and the coupon was 10,

00:23:38.457 --> 00:23:39.910
was that what it was?
 

00:23:39.910 --> 00:23:42.349
What?
 

00:23:42.349 --> 00:23:46.619
What was it?
 

00:23:46.619 --> 00:23:49.039
What was the homework problem?
 

00:23:49.039 --> 00:23:49.680
Student: 8 and 6.
 

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:50.430
Prof: 8 and 6.
 

00:23:50.430 --> 00:23:51.950
So this was 8 percent.
 

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:58.644
Might as well do this one,
6 here, yeah,

00:23:58.644 --> 00:24:04.140
6 percent, and this one was 8.
 

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:08.859
So what was the price
PV_0?

00:24:08.859 --> 00:24:12.980
What was PV_0?
 

00:24:12.980 --> 00:24:16.890
You've done this homework
problem, right?

00:24:16.890 --> 00:24:27.019
Does anyone remember what
number they got?

00:24:27.019 --> 00:24:29.029
Ben, do you remember the number?
 

00:24:29.029 --> 00:24:31.358
No.
 

00:24:31.358 --> 00:24:39.178
I'm counting on my trusty class
here to provide me all the

00:24:39.178 --> 00:24:40.549
numbers.
 

00:24:40.549 --> 00:24:41.690
It was what?
 

00:24:41.690 --> 00:24:43.578
Student: 108.4.
 

00:24:43.578 --> 00:24:45.170
Prof: Was that what it
was, 108.4?

00:24:45.170 --> 00:24:47.759
That's all?
 

00:24:47.759 --> 00:24:57.740
This was the price just 108.4?
 

00:24:57.740 --> 00:24:58.980
So 108.4, right.
 

00:24:58.980 --> 00:25:00.240
That's a high price.
 

00:25:00.240 --> 00:25:02.240
So it's way above par.
 

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:04.839
This is a bond that's worth
much more than 100.

00:25:04.839 --> 00:25:05.480
Why?
 

00:25:05.480 --> 00:25:08.686
Because the interest rate is 6
percent, but the coupon is 8 so

00:25:08.686 --> 00:25:10.368
this is called a premium bond.
 

00:25:10.368 --> 00:25:15.016
So if you look at the first
year the rate of return on the

00:25:15.016 --> 00:25:17.380
first year is 8 over 108.4.
 

00:25:17.380 --> 00:25:21.269
Now, is that more than 6
percent?

00:25:21.269 --> 00:25:25.400
It is way more than 6 percent,
8 over 108.4.

00:25:25.400 --> 00:25:34.663
It is way more than 6 percent
because 7 percent of this is

00:25:34.663 --> 00:25:38.890
going to be less than 8.
 

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:42.981
So it's more than 7 percent,
so this is greater than 7

00:25:42.981 --> 00:25:47.230
percent, and so it's certainly
bigger than 6 percent.

00:25:47.230 --> 00:25:50.431
So it sure looks like at the
end of the first year like this

00:25:50.431 --> 00:25:51.680
bond was an ace bond.
 

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:53.788
That's the kind of calls you
used to get.

00:25:53.788 --> 00:25:57.387
You still sometimes do get them
if you're a wealthy person and

00:25:57.387 --> 00:25:59.690
you actually answer calls like
this,

00:25:59.690 --> 00:26:02.229
which you don't of course,
but you can get some cold call

00:26:02.229 --> 00:26:04.788
from a sales person saying,
"We've got a fund and look

00:26:04.788 --> 00:26:05.598
how well it's doing.
 

00:26:05.598 --> 00:26:09.494
On this much investment last
year we got payments of 8

00:26:09.494 --> 00:26:10.230
dollars.
 

00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:12.717
That's more than 7 percent,
and look, everybody can see the

00:26:12.717 --> 00:26:15.075
interest rate is only 6 percent
and we did better than 7

00:26:15.075 --> 00:26:15.589
percent.
 

00:26:15.589 --> 00:26:16.598
We're doing great.
 

00:26:16.598 --> 00:26:18.308
Why don't you invest in our
fund?"

00:26:18.308 --> 00:26:21.451
But actually,
what the salesman hasn't told

00:26:21.451 --> 00:26:25.338
you is that the value of his
assets has gone down.

00:26:25.338 --> 00:26:29.394
So the present value
PV_1 must be less than

00:26:29.394 --> 00:26:33.372
PV_0,
because we know from this

00:26:33.372 --> 00:26:37.180
formula, the formula right up
here,

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:39.810
that 6 percent is going to be
the cash flow over

00:26:39.810 --> 00:26:42.722
PV_0 which is more
than 7 percent plus this

00:26:42.722 --> 00:26:44.472
difference,
and this difference,

00:26:44.472 --> 00:26:46.348
therefore, is going to have to
be negative.

00:26:46.348 --> 00:26:50.407
So what he didn't tell you was
that the fund lost value even

00:26:50.407 --> 00:26:53.847
though the first payment was
better than 6 percent,

00:26:53.847 --> 00:26:56.049
the market rate of interest.
 

00:26:56.049 --> 00:27:00.900
So that's the first example.
 

00:27:00.900 --> 00:27:07.680
Now, let's do another example.
 

00:27:07.680 --> 00:27:15.318
Suppose you have a--let's see
if I can write on this board.

00:27:15.318 --> 00:27:26.528
There's a famous trade called
the carry trade.

00:27:26.528 --> 00:27:30.101
Now, suppose the
forwards--suppose 1

00:27:30.101 --> 00:27:34.692
i^(F)_0 is 2 percent,
sort of like now,

00:27:34.692 --> 00:27:41.048
the 1 year yield,
and 1 i^(F)_t is 5

00:27:41.048 --> 00:27:47.200
percent,
for t greater than 1?

00:27:47.200 --> 00:27:50.748
So if you have a 1 year bond
it's going to pay--well,

00:27:50.748 --> 00:27:54.842
let's say it's 2 percent and
this is equal to 1 --can you see

00:27:54.842 --> 00:27:56.890
this or it's disappearing.
 

00:27:56.890 --> 00:28:01.053
So let's make the first two of
them be 2 percent,

00:28:01.053 --> 00:28:05.130
and this is for t greater than
or equal to 3.

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:09.200
So the interest rate is 2
percent and then it's going to

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:10.680
jump to 5 percent.
 

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:13.358
All right, so if you have a
2-year bond,

00:28:13.358 --> 00:28:22.181
a 2-year Treasury,
a 2-year bond might pay 2 and

00:28:22.181 --> 00:28:31.190
102 and the present value of
this equals 100,

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:37.480
the present value of the 2-year
bond.

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:44.042
But now maybe you've got a
longer bond that's a 5-year bond

00:28:44.042 --> 00:28:56.232
which pays coupons 4,
4,4, 104, so this is a 5-year

00:28:56.232 --> 00:29:00.973
bond,
and maybe its price is close to

00:29:00.973 --> 00:29:01.368
100.
 

