00:55:25.621 --> 00:55:29.630
interest in the country,
namely Social Security.

00:55:29.630 --> 00:55:32.630
What should we do about Social
Security?

00:55:32.630 --> 00:55:35.954
Now, it will turn out that you
can analyze the situation the

00:55:35.954 --> 00:55:38.380
same way we've just analyzed
these bonds.

00:55:38.380 --> 00:55:41.005
It's very simple to figure out
what the problem is and what

00:55:41.005 --> 00:55:43.483
went wrong,
yet very few people understand

00:55:43.483 --> 00:55:46.190
it, including most of our
politicians and,

00:55:46.190 --> 00:55:48.210
I'm sorry to say,
a lot of our economists.

00:55:48.210 --> 00:55:53.914
So I want to describe now in
the next class and a half the

00:55:53.914 --> 00:55:59.518
Social Security problem and how
to solve the problem,

00:55:59.518 --> 00:56:01.130
but also how to understand the
problem.

00:56:01.130 --> 00:56:04.023
You can't figure out the right
solution until you've understood

00:56:04.023 --> 00:56:05.050
what the problem is.
 

00:56:05.050 --> 00:56:07.809
So were there any questions?
 

00:56:07.809 --> 00:56:09.590
Before I start this,
were there any questions?

00:56:09.590 --> 00:56:10.210
I should have paused.
 

00:56:10.210 --> 00:56:13.614
Are there any questions about
the mortgage,

00:56:13.614 --> 00:56:17.262
or present value,
or how present value changes

00:56:17.262 --> 00:56:18.639
through time?
 

00:56:18.639 --> 00:56:20.773
So those ideas,
and marking to market,

00:56:20.773 --> 00:56:24.117
those are very important ideas
I think once you think about

00:56:24.117 --> 00:56:25.329
them not so hard.
 

00:56:25.329 --> 00:56:28.865
I'm now going to take exactly
those ideas and apply it to

00:56:28.865 --> 00:56:32.340
Social Security where the public
is totally baffled,

00:56:32.340 --> 00:56:34.610
but all you have to do is apply
the same thinking.

00:56:34.610 --> 00:56:37.518
So Social Security is supposed
to be in a terrible crisis.

00:56:37.518 --> 00:56:42.159
That's what they always tell
you.

00:56:42.159 --> 00:56:44.699
It was a big campaign issue in
2000,

00:56:44.699 --> 00:56:46.530
you probably were too young to
remember that,

00:56:46.530 --> 00:56:50.117
but there were three debates
between Gore and Bush in which

00:56:50.117 --> 00:56:53.768
Gore grimaced and everybody
thought he wasn't a good guy and

00:56:53.768 --> 00:56:55.440
so they voted for Bush.
 

00:56:55.440 --> 00:56:58.590
He was mostly grimacing about
Social Security.

00:56:58.590 --> 00:57:01.949
And then in 2000--well,
I'll get to the future.

00:57:01.949 --> 00:57:06.429
So anyway, in those debates
three mistakes were made.

00:57:06.429 --> 00:57:11.126
So Bush argued that the returns
on Social Security were

00:57:11.126 --> 00:57:12.780
disastrously low.
 

00:57:12.780 --> 00:57:20.425
He said the whole program is in
a terrible crisis and we've got

00:57:20.425 --> 00:57:24.619
to privatize to save the system.
 

00:57:24.619 --> 00:57:26.079
How did it get into the crisis?
 

00:57:26.079 --> 00:57:28.514
Well, it wasn't clear exactly
how it got into the crisis,

00:57:28.514 --> 00:57:31.034
but it seems like the baby
boomers had something to do with

00:57:31.034 --> 00:57:31.340
it.
 

00:57:31.340 --> 00:57:33.644
They're all getting old and
they're going to have to get

00:57:33.644 --> 00:57:35.280
these huge Social Security
payments,

00:57:35.280 --> 00:57:37.293
and that's why we're in the
crisis because the baby boomers

00:57:37.293 --> 00:57:37.920
are getting old.
 

00:57:37.920 --> 00:57:41.789
It's all my fault,
or my generation's fault.

00:57:41.789 --> 00:57:45.387
Then the third mistake was Gore
said, "Well,

00:57:45.387 --> 00:57:48.159
it's impossible to
privatize."

00:57:48.159 --> 00:57:51.498
Privatize means take the money
that your parents are paying in

00:57:51.498 --> 00:57:54.070
Social Security and that you'll
start to pay;

00:57:54.070 --> 00:57:57.670
instead of putting it into the
fund that's being used somehow,

00:57:57.670 --> 00:57:59.420
you don't probably know exactly
how,

00:57:59.420 --> 00:58:03.289
instead of doing that,
take that money and say it's

00:58:03.289 --> 00:58:05.070
the taxpayer's money.
 

00:58:05.070 --> 00:58:05.929
It's your money.
 

00:58:05.929 --> 00:58:08.090
You can put it in the stock
market if you want.

00:58:08.090 --> 00:58:11.454
So that's what Bush wanted to
do, privatize Social Security,

00:58:11.454 --> 00:58:14.590
say your tax contributions
should go into a stock market

00:58:14.590 --> 00:58:16.130
with your name on them.
 

00:58:16.130 --> 00:58:17.989
And Gore said,
"Well, that's impossible.

00:58:17.989 --> 00:58:20.373
If you privatize,
what are the old people today

00:58:20.373 --> 00:58:21.099
going to do?
 

00:58:21.099 --> 00:58:22.449
Where are they going to get the
payments?

00:58:22.449 --> 00:58:26.072
You can't privatize Social
Security and take today's young

00:58:26.072 --> 00:58:28.867
tax contributions to Social
Security and say,

00:58:28.867 --> 00:58:31.409
'You young guys,
there's your money.

00:58:31.409 --> 00:58:34.360
You can keep them in the stock
market,' and at the same time

00:58:34.360 --> 00:58:36.960
pay the old retirees,
so Bush must not know what he's

00:58:36.960 --> 00:58:38.159
talking about."
 

00:58:38.159 --> 00:58:40.460
So that also was wrong.
 

00:58:40.460 --> 00:58:44.313
So those three things,
that Social Security is going

00:58:44.313 --> 00:58:47.610
to give terrible returns,
it must be it's wasting money,

00:58:47.610 --> 00:58:50.012
something's horribly wrong with
it and the only way to save it

00:58:50.012 --> 00:58:50.880
is to privatize it.
 

00:58:50.880 --> 00:58:52.380
That's Bush's main claim.
 

00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:54.179
Blame it all on the baby
generation,

00:58:54.179 --> 00:58:56.385
that's everybody's claim,
and Gore saying you can't

00:58:56.385 --> 00:58:58.679
privatize without screwing
today's young [correction:

00:58:58.679 --> 00:58:59.650
today's retirees].
 

00:58:59.650 --> 00:59:02.969
All three of those things sound
pretty convincing and yet

00:59:02.969 --> 00:59:04.510
they're all three wrong.
 

00:59:04.510 --> 00:59:07.742
So I want to explain the system
to you and help you understand

00:59:07.742 --> 00:59:09.626
it,
and then I have a policy

00:59:09.626 --> 00:59:13.480
recommendation you'll get next
class which most people don't

00:59:13.480 --> 00:59:17.079
agree with,
so you probably won't either,

00:59:17.079 --> 00:59:22.768
but I'll warn you when we get
to a point that's controversial.

00:59:22.768 --> 00:59:26.425
So everything I'm going to say
in the first 90 minutes is going

00:59:26.425 --> 00:59:27.840
to be uncontroversial.
 

00:59:27.840 --> 00:59:30.166
Not everybody knows it,
but I think it's obviously just

00:59:30.166 --> 00:59:31.030
a matter of logic.
 

00:59:31.030 --> 00:59:34.320
And then my conclusion about
what to do, you can criticize

00:59:34.320 --> 00:59:34.610
it.
 

00:59:34.610 --> 00:59:37.125
I think it's a matter of logic
too, but I admit most people

00:59:37.125 --> 00:59:38.079
don't agree with it.
 

00:59:38.079 --> 00:59:42.775
So now, in 2005 if nothing else
Bush was tremendously

00:59:42.775 --> 00:59:43.949
consistent.
 

00:59:43.949 --> 00:59:47.003
So whatever he told you he was
going to do no matter how

00:59:47.003 --> 00:59:48.780
wrong-handed it was he did it.
 

00:59:48.780 --> 00:59:51.987
So he said in the debates that
he wanted to privatize Social

00:59:51.987 --> 00:59:54.380
Security and sure enough he kept
his word.

00:59:54.380 --> 00:59:56.230
He launched a huge program.
 

00:59:56.230 --> 00:59:58.949
That's how he started right
after the 2004 election.

00:59:58.949 --> 01:00:01.157
His first initiative,
you might remember,

01:00:01.157 --> 01:00:03.639
was we've got to privatize
Social Security.

01:00:03.639 --> 01:00:08.152
He went on a 60-day,
60-city tour to kick off his

01:00:08.152 --> 01:00:09.469
second term.
 

01:00:09.469 --> 01:00:12.762
So after the 2004 election
privatizing Social Security was

01:00:12.762 --> 01:00:13.630
a huge issue.
 

01:00:13.630 --> 01:00:16.710
In the 2008 election it was
still a big issue.

01:00:16.710 --> 01:00:19.219
McCain said sort of what Bush
said.

01:00:19.219 --> 01:00:22.030
"I want young workers to
be able to if they choose,

01:00:22.030 --> 01:00:24.420
to take part of their own money
which is their taxes,

01:00:24.420 --> 01:00:26.360
their money that's getting
taxed and getting put into

01:00:26.360 --> 01:00:28.182
Social Security,
I want them to have their own

01:00:28.182 --> 01:00:30.409
account and put it into the
stock market with their name on

01:00:30.409 --> 01:00:30.869
it."
 

01:00:30.869 --> 01:00:35.440
And Obama said he's totally
against that.

01:00:35.440 --> 01:00:36.670
That was 2008.
 

01:00:36.670 --> 01:00:40.677
Recently, of course,
the public has made another

01:00:40.677 --> 01:00:41.530
mistake.
 

01:00:41.530 --> 01:00:45.389
So everybody is saying now,
"Oh, the financial crisis.

01:00:45.389 --> 01:00:47.550
We better not talk about Social
Security anymore."

01:00:47.550 --> 01:00:49.989
Nobody's talking about Social
Security.

01:00:49.989 --> 01:00:53.365
They're saying, "Well,
could you have imagined what

01:00:53.365 --> 01:00:56.188
would have happened had we
privatized as Bush wanted us to

01:00:56.188 --> 01:00:58.018
do and the stock market
collapsed?

01:00:58.018 --> 01:00:59.530
Everybody would have lost all
their money.

01:00:59.530 --> 01:01:03.054
What a disaster that would have
been, and it would have ruined

01:01:03.054 --> 01:01:03.980
the old."
 

01:01:03.980 --> 01:01:05.489
This sounds pretty persuasive.
 

01:01:05.489 --> 01:01:08.829
So Krugman wrote a column
saying, "A bullet dodged.

01:01:08.829 --> 01:01:11.039
What would have happened if
Bush had succeeded?

01:01:11.039 --> 01:01:13.340
All the old people would be
broke now."

01:01:13.340 --> 01:01:17.411
And Robert Reich who was in the
Clinton Administration sort of

01:01:17.411 --> 01:01:21.349
more or less said the same thing
that it'd be a disaster.

01:01:21.349 --> 01:01:24.320
Now, the Obama Administration,
by the way, hasn't stopped

01:01:24.320 --> 01:01:26.018
talking about Social Security.
 

01:01:26.018 --> 01:01:28.670
So their director,
he's the Director of the White

01:01:28.670 --> 01:01:31.485
House Office of the Budget,
so this is an incredibly

01:01:31.485 --> 01:01:33.530
important position,
Peter Orszag.

01:01:33.530 --> 01:01:36.934
He's the son of--there's a math
professor here,

01:01:36.934 --> 01:01:38.489
Orszag, his father.
 

01:01:38.489 --> 01:01:41.719
So he's a friend of mine,
the son.

01:01:41.719 --> 01:01:45.860
He said once healthcare reform
is in place the U.S.

01:01:45.860 --> 01:01:48.282
can then focus on other
important things,

01:01:48.282 --> 01:01:50.039
especially Social Security.
 

01:01:50.039 --> 01:01:52.855
So Obama wants to do something
about it, but he just doesn't

01:01:52.855 --> 01:01:53.809
want to privatize.
 

01:01:53.809 --> 01:01:56.333
So it's a big problem and
everything everybody says about

01:01:56.333 --> 01:01:57.280
it seems plausible.
 

01:01:57.280 --> 01:02:00.820
Now, just to continue along the
plausibility of it,

01:02:00.820 --> 01:02:04.360
so Bush says what he really
wants to do is--

01:02:04.360 --> 01:02:07.221
why private accounts are a
better thing is that if you put

01:02:07.221 --> 01:02:09.429
the money in private accounts it
can grow.

01:02:09.429 --> 01:02:11.871
You can get a greater rate of
return than the current system

01:02:11.871 --> 01:02:12.699
which is terrible.
 

01:02:12.699 --> 01:02:16.835
If you were a young person by
putting your Social Security tax

01:02:16.835 --> 01:02:21.038
money aside in a private account
you'll be able to get a better

01:02:21.038 --> 01:02:24.902
rate of return on your money
than the government could get

01:02:24.902 --> 01:02:26.530
you on your money.
 

01:02:26.530 --> 01:02:28.409
So why would you just want to
give it to the government?

01:02:28.409 --> 01:02:31.891
It's for your retirement and
you'll be able to pass that

01:02:31.891 --> 01:02:35.943
money along to your children and
grandchildren if you want at the

01:02:35.943 --> 01:02:36.449
end.
 

01:02:36.449 --> 01:02:39.251
And best of all the money's
yours and the government can't

01:02:39.251 --> 01:02:39.989
take it away.
 

01:02:39.989 --> 01:02:43.889
So that's what Bush says and
he's said many times.

01:02:43.889 --> 01:02:46.849
So there's one sense in which
he's right.

01:02:46.849 --> 01:02:51.760
So let's look at the returns
people got on Social Security.

01:02:51.760 --> 01:02:53.280
Now, what is a return?
 

01:02:53.280 --> 01:02:54.809
We know what the rate of return
is.

01:02:54.809 --> 01:02:56.090
How do they calculate it?
 

01:02:56.090 --> 01:03:00.909
You can go back to people born
starting in 1878.

01:03:00.909 --> 01:03:03.047
Social Security,
as you'll see in a second,

01:03:03.047 --> 01:03:05.489
I'm going to give you the
history, began 1939.

01:03:05.489 --> 01:03:12.244
So these people in 1878 they're
60 when Social Security's

01:03:12.244 --> 01:03:16.949
beginning, if my arithmetic is
right.

01:03:16.949 --> 01:03:19.420
So they're 60 at that point.
 

01:03:19.420 --> 01:03:22.210
So you can look at all these
people and you can say,

01:03:22.210 --> 01:03:25.440
for every generation in the
past, you can say how much money

01:03:25.440 --> 01:03:27.519
did they pay when they were
young?

01:03:27.519 --> 01:03:28.579
They paid taxes.
 

01:03:28.579 --> 01:03:32.460
So they got negative 12.4,
that's the tax rate.

01:03:32.460 --> 01:03:34.652
Negative 12.4,
they did that a bunch of years

01:03:34.652 --> 01:03:37.543
when they were young and then
they started getting payments

01:03:37.543 --> 01:03:42.309
when they were old,
24,24, 20 something like that.

01:03:42.309 --> 01:03:45.619
Those are the payments when
they're old.

01:03:45.619 --> 01:03:47.969
So there are negative ones at
the beginning and positive ones

01:03:47.969 --> 01:03:48.480
at the end.
 

01:03:48.480 --> 01:03:51.481
You can calculate the internal
rate of return,

01:03:51.481 --> 01:03:55.150
the yield, the thing that makes
this present value 0.

01:03:55.150 --> 01:03:55.900
We know how to do that.
 

01:03:55.900 --> 01:03:57.070
We've done it.
 

01:03:57.070 --> 01:03:59.139
So people have done this.
 

01:03:59.139 --> 01:04:02.967
So there's a guy named Limmer,
Limmer or Leemer from the

01:04:02.967 --> 01:04:06.932
Social Security Administration
who did these calculations,

01:04:06.932 --> 01:04:09.159
prompted a little bit by me.
 

01:04:09.159 --> 01:04:12.648
So I should say that a lot of
the reason I got started

01:04:12.648 --> 01:04:16.862
thinking about this is I got put
on a Presidential Panel to study

01:04:16.862 --> 01:04:20.876
Social Security Reform in the
Clinton Administration and every

01:04:20.876 --> 01:04:23.840
Democrat was matched with a
Republican.

01:04:23.840 --> 01:04:25.534
So the two chairmen,
one Democrat,

01:04:25.534 --> 01:04:27.798
one Republican,
all the way along there was

01:04:27.798 --> 01:04:30.869
Democrat and Republican,
and after Bush got elected all

01:04:30.869 --> 01:04:33.480
the Democrats got kicked off the
committee.

01:04:33.480 --> 01:04:40.690
But anyway, so in any case here
are the rates of return.

01:04:40.690 --> 01:04:43.606
For people who are old when the
program began,

01:04:43.606 --> 01:04:46.782
they got sensational rates of
returns, 40 percent,

01:04:46.782 --> 01:04:49.570
30 percent, incredible rates of
return.

01:04:49.570 --> 01:04:54.036
As the generations get younger
and younger the returns go lower

01:04:54.036 --> 01:04:57.349
and lower and they're down now
to 2 percent.

01:04:57.349 --> 01:04:59.869
These are a forecast of these
rates of returns.

01:04:59.869 --> 01:05:02.463
And so let's see,
you're 20, say,

01:05:02.463 --> 01:05:04.329
something on average.
 

01:05:04.329 --> 01:05:08.833
You were born in 1990,
something like that or around

01:05:08.833 --> 01:05:09.539
there.
 

01:05:09.539 --> 01:05:11.530
So here's your rate of return.
 

01:05:11.530 --> 01:05:13.900
It's down here, right?
 

01:05:13.900 --> 01:05:16.719
It's 2 percent,
and there it is blown up.

01:05:16.719 --> 01:05:18.010
It's under 2 percent.
 

01:05:18.010 --> 01:05:20.163
So these are the people from
1924 to 2002,

01:05:20.163 --> 01:05:21.949
so you're right at the end
here.

01:05:21.949 --> 01:05:23.730
That's your rate of return
blown up.

01:05:23.730 --> 01:05:26.599
You can only expect 1 and a
half or 2 percent.

01:05:26.599 --> 01:05:27.929
So George Bush is right.
 

01:05:27.929 --> 01:05:30.710
The rate of return on Social
Security is terrible.

01:05:30.710 --> 01:05:34.568
If you look at the taxes that
you put in, and you look at the

01:05:34.568 --> 01:05:38.492
benefits that you can expect to
get your generation is getting

01:05:38.492 --> 01:05:39.780
totally screwed.
 

01:05:39.780 --> 01:05:43.045
So now if you look
historically--this was done in

01:05:43.045 --> 01:05:45.166
1994,
so the number's a little

01:05:45.166 --> 01:05:48.572
bit--it's not quite as dramatic,
but it hasn't changed as much

01:05:48.572 --> 01:05:49.139
as you think.
 

01:05:49.139 --> 01:05:52.559
From money put in the stock
market between '26 and 2004,

01:05:52.559 --> 01:05:56.164
that's before the crash of '29,
so I should have gotten the

01:05:56.164 --> 01:05:58.280
number after the recent crash.
 

01:05:58.280 --> 01:05:59.380
It doesn't change that much.
 

01:05:59.380 --> 01:06:02.420
Before the crash of '29 you
looked at keeping your money in

01:06:02.420 --> 01:06:04.989
the stock market,
just leaving it there for all

01:06:04.989 --> 01:06:07.900
that time,
after inflation you'd get 9.1

01:06:07.900 --> 01:06:09.159
percent return.
 

01:06:09.159 --> 01:06:13.835
On treasury bonds you get 2.7
percent return and yet on Social

01:06:13.835 --> 01:06:17.440
Security you're going to get
under 2 percent.

01:06:17.440 --> 01:06:20.041
So George Bush says,
"Look, put it in the stock

01:06:20.041 --> 01:06:20.500
market.
 

01:06:20.500 --> 01:06:21.550
Get 9 percent."
 

01:06:21.550 --> 01:06:24.829
We had a little disaster here,
so maybe it's 7 percent.

01:06:24.829 --> 01:06:26.710
"Put it in the stock
market and get 7 percent.

01:06:26.710 --> 01:06:28.750
Why be satisfied with 2 percent?
 

01:06:28.750 --> 01:06:29.539
There's something wrong.
 

01:06:29.539 --> 01:06:32.670
We've got to privatize,
put an end to this."

01:06:32.670 --> 01:06:36.099
So there seems to be something
to what he is saying.

01:06:36.099 --> 01:06:39.889
So now you look at what's going
on with Social Security.

01:06:39.889 --> 01:06:41.360
So what happens in Social
Security?

01:06:41.360 --> 01:06:43.980
I'm going to explain the whole
history and how it works here.

01:06:43.980 --> 01:06:50.210
What happens is you pay taxes,
12.4 percent tax.

01:06:50.210 --> 01:06:51.349
You probably know that.
 

01:06:51.349 --> 01:06:54.228
Everybody's paying taxes on the
money they make and then there

01:06:54.228 --> 01:06:55.880
are benefits that are being
paid.

01:06:55.880 --> 01:06:58.713
Now, the benefits are
not--there's a formula for

01:06:58.713 --> 01:07:02.152
benefits which doesn't have
anything to do with the amount

01:07:02.152 --> 01:07:05.186
of taxes being paid,
so at the present time the

01:07:05.186 --> 01:07:07.300
taxes are bigger than the
benefits.

01:07:07.300 --> 01:07:08.849
So where does the extra money
go?

